[1] Thailand, H5N1
Date: Tue, 13 Jul 2004
From: Jamal Hassan <jamal@jphvri.po.my>
Source: AFP via TheStarOnLine, Malaysia, 10 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://202.186.86.35/news/story.asp?file=/2004/7/10/asia/8410778&newspage=Search>
Thailand to cull wild storks to end bird flu
---------------------------------------------
Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra yesterday ordered the culling of wild
storks which he said were responsible for 2 fresh bird flu outbreaks in the
kingdom.
"These latest outbreaks of bird flu were caused by storks which are very
difficult to eradicate, but I have ordered the Natural Resources and
Environment Ministry to quickly cull all storks," he told reporters.
The culling of the birds, which he said were suspected carriers of the flu,
was to begin immediately, he added.
This week Thai officials confirmed 2 outbreaks of bird flu at a poultry
farm in Ayutthaya province and in home-grown chickens in Pathum Thai
province, both in central Thailand, but insisted that the outbreaks were
under control.
Thaksin conceded that environmentalists were likely to protest against the
move to eradicate the birds, but he stressed that public health took
precedence over wildlife as the country moved to contain the potentially
deadly virus.
--
Jamal Hassan,
Research Officer, Virology Section,
Veterinary Research Institute (VRI),
Perak Darul Ridzuan,
Malaysia.
<jamal@jphvri.po.my>
[Culling wild birds to control avian influenza is an extreme,
highly controversial and most probably ineffective measure. See in
"Wildlife Management", FAO/OIE's Animal Health Special Report - Technical
Consultations, posting 20040318.0750, stating: "Wild birds should not be
depopulated in an attempt to control avian influenza but separation, as
much as possible, should be attempted". See further in [2]. - Mod. AS].
