[3] Thailand & Vietnam, H5N1
Date: Wed, 14 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Nation, 14 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://www.nationmultimedia.com/page.news.php3?clid=2&id=117259&usrsess=1>
Bird flu confirmed in 7 provinces
-----------------------------------------------------
The government yesterday confirmed a fresh outbreak of bird flu in 7
provinces as dozens of chicken deaths in Bangkok raised concerns that the
virus may have reached the capital.
Ayutthaya, Pathum Thani, Suphan Buri, Angthong, Nakhon Sawan, Uttaradit and
Sukhothai all have new H5N1 bird-flu infections, Deputy Prime Minister
Chaturon Chaisang said.
"But we have taken relevant actions to control the situation", he said.
According to Chaturon, chickens in outbreak hotspots were being culled and
their owners would be compensated within 2 weeks.
The deputy PM seemed confident authorities would be able to tackle this
latest outbreak due to their extensive experience battling the disease
earlier this year. He added that this new round of infections was small in
scope.
Meanwhile, Bangkok livestock chief Padung Sutecha said he had received
reports of suspicious chicken deaths in Bangkok districts Thawee Watthana
and Don Muang, and the border area between Min Buri and Khlong Sam districts.
"We have collected samples and sent them to the lab. We should know the
results within 8 days",he said.
He added that the number of dead chickens numbered only in the dozens,
while other birds remained healthy.
Livestock Development Department director-general Yukol Limlamthong said
relevant authorities were monitoring several other provinces where new
suspected bird-flu infections had been reported.
"We are waiting for lab tests, and I don't think all the cases will
necessarily be bird flu", he said.
When asked about a farmer who smuggled 2000 of his chickens from Nakhon
Sawan, Agriculture and Cooperatives Minister Somsak Thepsuthin said
officials had managed to trace the offender and cull his fowl.
"We also filed a complaint with police against this farmer", Somsak added.
Yukol said relevant officials had the duty to report any suspected bird-flu
cases to provincial governors and public-health chiefs, and relevant
central agencies within 24 hours of detection.
Any farm where more than 10 per cent of fowls die mysteriously would
warrant attention and culling.
"The culling and the ban of fowl movements must be enforced if fowls appear
to be infected with avian influenza",he said.
Despite Yukol's insistence that Thailand does not require a bird-flu
vaccine to deal with this current outbreak, he admitted his department
planned to seek a Bt60 to Bt70-million budget [approximately $1.5 to $1.7
million USD] for the establishment of a vaccine-development laboratory.
"We have to prepare a long-term solution", he said.
The director-general believes the development of a vaccine will take a few
years.
Yukol confirmed that blood tests from chickens across the country would be
implemented late this month to determine which farms were infected with the
virus and which farmers had broken the law by injecting fowls with the vaccine.
"We will carry out the culling at farms where the infections are detected",
he said.
He added that provincial livestock officials nationwide would today attend
a meeting in Bangkok for a refreshment seminar on how to efficiently
prevent the spread of the disease.
In Hanoi, Bui Quang Anh, director of Vietnam's agriculture ministry's
animal health department, said poultry samples from the south of the
country had detected the virus but officials had the disease - which killed
16 people in Vietnam earlier this year - under control.
"Test results from random samples showed the fowls were infected with the
H5N1 strain of avian influenza", the director said. "The virus was leftover
from the previous outbreak because of our incomplete treatment of infected
farms".
Anh told Reuters that the H5N1 finding came 3 days ago and about 10 000
poultry - mostly chickens - in Mekong Delta provinces had been culled.
Vietnamese officials said last month that preliminary tests found only the
weaker H5 strain of the virus.
[Byline: Piyanart Srivalo, Saowalak Pumyaem]
