[4] Viet Nam, H5N1
Date: 13 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AFP via iAfrica.com, 13 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://iafrica.com/news/worldnews/334456.htm>

Vietnam confirms return of bird flu
-------------------------------------
Vietnam confirmed Tuesday that fresh outbreaks of bird flu were caused by
the lethal strain of the disease that killed 16 people in the country
earlier this year.
Agriculture ministry spokesperson Bui Quang Anh said tests carried out by
experts from the southern regional veterinary department in Ho Chi Minh
City had revealed the presence of the H5N1 virus.
"Vietnamese experts have discovered H5N1 in samples taken from poultry in
affected areas," he told AFP.
The state-run Sai Gon Giai Phong newspaper reported Tuesday [13 Jul 2004]
that bird flu outbreaks have occurred in 14 districts in 7 southern
provinces and cities since mid-April [2004].
A total of 22 470 chickens, 169 ducks, and 13 000 quails have either died
or been destroyed, the daily said. Anh refused to confirm the figures.
Last week the government was forced to defend its much criticised 30 Mar
2004 declaration that the country was free of bird flu.
"I think the announcement was correct and based on legal foundations. The
recurrence of any outbreaks may have occurred for a variety of reasons,"
foreign ministry spokesperson Le Dung told reporters.
"As you may know bird flu has appeared in several countries in Asia,
including China, Thailand, and Vietnam," he added.
The 30 March declaration, which came just 15 days after the disease claimed
its 16th fatality, prompted criticism from international experts that Hanoi
was acting prematurely and recklessly.
The World Health Organisation warned that it could take months, probably
years to eliminate the H5N1 virus from the environment.
International experts also criticised the government for its lack of
cooperation in tackling the disease and charged it with being more
concerned at putting its poultry industry back on a sound footing.
More than 44 million poultry died or were slaughtered across Vietnam as a
result of the bird flu, which was detected in 57 of its 64 provinces during
the major outbreak earlier this year.
Meanwhile, the Sai Gon Giai Phong said that since the beginning of July
[2004]authorities in the northern province of Lang Son, which borders
China, have confiscated and destroyed more than 2 tonnes of poultry [live
animals? carcasses?] smuggled into the country.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The unfolding renewed epizootic in East-Asia is a cause for great concern.
Since the attempt to eradicate the disease by stamping-out has not proven
to achieve the expected eradication of the disease from the poultry
industry in some of the affected countries, reverting to vaccination in
such countries deserves to be reconsidered. The north-Italian experience
might serve as an example. Illegal use of uncertified, probably smuggled
vaccines of which the safety and efficacy are -- at best -- unknown, is not
only a breach of law but may play a role in the spread of the disease. -
Mod.AS].
